article.description:
Sixth-ranked Connecticut followed its
perfect season with a less-than-perfect start, but got 18 points
from freshman Nicole Wolff and beat Wright State 85-39 Friday
night.
article.headline: Taurasi finishes with 15 points in UConn's victory
article.linkText: Huskies bounce back from rough start to rout Wright St.
article.story:
STORRS, Conn. (AP) -- Sue Bird was back. So were Tamika Williams,
Swin Cash and Asjha Jones.

	   The former All-Americans took center court as defending champion
(No. 5 ESPN/USA Today, No. 6 AP) Connecticut unveiled the NCAA championship banner Friday night. The
stars backed out of the spotlight to make way for a court full of
fresh faces. And the rookies didn't disappoint.

	   Freshman Nicole Wolff debuted with 18 points to lead UConn to an
85-39 win over Wright State. Wolff, the daughter of Boston
University men's coach Dennis Wolff, made four of five 3-pointers
and was 4-of-4 from the foul line.

	   Freshman Ann Strother, a Colorado prep star and national player
of the year, finished with 11 points, 11 rebounds and three blocks.
Diana Taurasi, the lone starter from the last season's 39-0
national championship squad, finished with 15 points and seven
assists.

	   ``We were a little wound up,'' Wolff said. ``Once we slowed
down, I think we clicked.''

	   The Huskies opened the game with three straight turnovers and
finished with 25. They relied on 5-of-5 free-throw shooting and a
3-pointer from Wolff to scratch out a 10-6 lead in the first 6
minutes.

	   ``I don't know what to feel,'' UConn coach Geno Auriemma said.
``It was one of those `are you happy because we're getting shots?
Or are you miserable because we're missing layups?'''

	   The Raiders, also opening their season, pressured Taurasi from
the start, and her supporting cast of two freshmen and two
sophomores had trouble handling the ball in the early minutes.

	   ``The first couple of minutes we were playing ahead of
ourselves,'' Taurasi said. ``As long as everyone keeps their head
up and keeps being confident with the ball and making shots, we're
going to be OK.''

	   Taurasi didn't make her first basket _ a backdoor layup _ until
there was 13:55 left in the first half. Her leaner two minutes
later kicked off a 15-2 run, and UConn was in control the rest of
the way.

	   UConn dominated inside, outscoring the Raiders 50-14 in the post
and holding a 51-25 edge on the boards. Jessica Moore led UConn
with 13 rebounds.

	   Moore and Ashley Battle scored 12 points apiece, and Battle had
a team-high three steals.

	   Tiffany Webb, the only Raider in double figures, led Wright
State with 16 points.

	   ``Our biggest thing was to come in and stick to our system and
work on what we need to work on. It's great to play a team like
UConn,'' Wright State coach Bridgett Williams said.

	   It was only the second meeting of the two teams. UConn posted a
58-point win over the Raiders last season in Dayton. The Huskies
are 21-8 in season openers.

	   Once his young team ran off opening-night jitters, Auriemma
liked what he saw.
	   
``The biggest thing is playing games ... being out on the
court,'' he said. ``The more they do that, the better they are
going to feel. Right now it's all about getting them comfortable.''
